.TH "runit" "8" 
.SH NAME
runit \- a UNIX process no 1
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]runit\f[R]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\f[B]runit\f[R] must be run as Unix process no 1.
It performs the system\[aq]s booting, running, and shutdown in three
stages:
.SH STAGE 1
\f[B]runit\f[R] runs \f[I]/etc/runit/1\f[R] and waits for it to
terminate.
The system\[aq]s one time tasks are done here.
\f[I]/etc/runit/1\f[R] has full control of \f[I]/dev/console\f[R] to be
able to start an emergency shell if the one time initialization tasks
fail.
If \f[I]/etc/runit/1\f[R] crashes, or exits 100, \f[B]runit\f[R] will
skip stage 2 and enter stage 3.
.SH STAGE 2
\f[B]runit\f[R] runs \f[I]/etc/runit/2\f[R], which should not return
until system shutdown; if it crashes, or exits 111, it will be
restarted.
Normally \f[I]/etc/runit/2\f[R] starts \f[B]runsvdir\f[R](8).
\f[B]runit\f[R] is able to handle the ctrl\-alt\-del keyboard request in
stage 2, see below.
.SH STAGE 3
If \f[B]runit\f[R] is told to shutdown the system, or stage 2 returns,
it terminates stage 2 if it is running, and runs \f[I]/etc/runit/3\f[R].
The systems tasks to shutdown and possibly halt or reboot the system are
done here.
If stage 3 returns, \f[B]runit\f[R] checks if the file
\f[I]/etc/runit/reboot\f[R] exists and has the execute by owner
permission set.
If so, the system is rebooted, it\[aq]s halted otherwise.
If \f[I]/etc/runit/nosync\f[R] exists, \f[B]runit\f[R] doesn\[aq]t
invoke sync().
This is useful in vservers.
.SH CTRL\-ALT\-DEL
If \f[B]runit\f[R] receives the ctrl\-alt\-del keyboard request and the
file \f[I]/etc/runit/ctrlaltdel\f[R] exists and has the execute by owner
permission set, \f[B]runit\f[R] runs \f[I]/etc/runit/ctrlaltdel\f[R],
waits for it to terminate, and then sends itself a CONT signal.
.SH SIGNALS
\f[B]runit\f[R] only accepts signals in stage 2.
.PP
If \f[B]runit\f[R] receives a CONT signal and the file
\f[I]/etc/runit/stopit\f[R] exists and has the execute by owner
permission set, \f[B]runit\f[R] is told to shutdown the system.
.PP
If \f[B]runit\f[R] receives an INT signal, a ctrl\-alt\-del keyboard
request is triggered.
